Let's start with defining and unpacking lust

Lust is one of the 7 cardinal sins which are the major vices that humans are suceptible to

They include gluttony, pride, greed, sloth (laziness), envy, wrath and lust

The primary Greek word for lust in the bible is epithymia, meaning a strong desire, craving or longing

Those words alone are neutral until context is applied. A strong desire and longing for God is not a sin but a craving for power or a craving for sexual behaviour with a woman outside of marriage is a sin


Lust is often thought of as unrestrained sexual craving, but the bible describes lust as a consuming, selfish desire that disregards God's will so it applies beyond just the sexual

In 1 John 2:16 John says "For all that is in the world - the desires of the flesh and the desires of the eyes and pride of life - is not from the Father but is from this world"

John is explaining 3 different categories of lust here

Desires of the flesh where we crave physical gratification which includes but isn't limited to sexual cravings

Desires of the eyes being covetous desires to possess things when we see them which might be out of a lack of contentment

Pride of life being the obsession with status, power or self importance


It's important to acknowledge that as humans have natural desires

For example, the desire for sexual intimacy in marriage

When those natural desires are corrupted they drift into lust which can lead to objectification, greed and the pursuit of what is forbidden

Objectification here refers to a disregard of the dignity and humanity of another person, viewing them simply as a tool for personal pleasure

What is the opposite of lust? self control, discipline or contentment

The opposite of lust is conquering our primal physical desires with discipline, moderation and self control

Lets read scripture and see what Jesus has to say about lust in sermon on the mount



--> Read verses 27 - 30

Once again, Jesus begins with "you have heard that it was said, but..."

He's saying that you were told this but I'm here to clarity misinterpretations and expand the meaning of the words to raise the bar

People were being taught the 7th commandment which forbids adultery and demands that people respect the sanctity of marriage but Jesus is saying that is the bare minimum and a low bar

The law says do not commit adultery but Jesus is going deeper into the intent of the commandment and setting a higher expectation

This is very similar to what we covered last week when Jesus spoke about anger. He said that its not enough to not murder others because being angry with them is like murdering them in our heart

It's not enough to simply avoid adultery because if a man looks at a woman with lustful intent, he is comitting adultery with her in his heart

In verse 29 Jesus says that if your eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw it away because its better to lose an eye than to be thrown into hell for eternity

Better to go to heaven with one eye than to go into hell with 2 eyes

Similarly, he says that if your hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away. Better to be without a hand than to be thrown into hell

Jesus is saying that our eyes tempt us to sin and our hands are used to commit all kinds of sins

He uses an overeggageration when he says to tear our our eye or cut off our hand to emphasize the importance of holding desires at bay to maintain loyalty to our spouse and to God

Seems to me like lust begins in our heart. That then leads to lust in our eye, then lust in our hand, then adultery

Intead of just curing symptoms of lust which can be thoughts, actions or even adultery in the most extreme case, Jesus is asking us to eliminate the disease at its root by targeting and conquering lust in our heart

We shouldn't just focus myopically on the action. Let's focus on the root of it. Let's not even allow the seed of lust to germinate

Jared Halverson had a great metaphor

Think of high jump. The higher the bar is, the harder it is to clear

Moses set a low bar. Just don't commit adultery

Jesus sets a higher bar by saying don't even have a lustful eye. Don't have lustful thoughts

The highest bar is to eliminate lust in your heart

Jared also said: if you saw it, its not your fault. If you look and dwell on what you saw, that's the problem

Repenting of every lustful thought is like constantly trimming weeds

Eliminating lust in your heart is like uprooting the base of the weed so it's eliminated for good


If we look at today's world, we can see lust everywhere

Pornography is rampant and addiction is common. The word pornea in greek translates to sexual immorality or prostitution. Pornography translates directory into porne meaning prostitute and grapho meaning to write 

Originally referred to descriptions of prostitutes

"Sex sells" is a marketing adage meaning that using sexual themes, imagery, or innuendo in advertisements grabs consumer attention and increases the likelihood of a product being purchased

Modern marketing is very good at using the human propensity toward sinful lust to grab our attention and make us want things

Just imagine a sports car ad with a man joined by a scantily dressed woman. The message there might be that if you have this car, you will attract beautiful women

Lust is used in movies and entertainment to capture out attention to such an extent that it's almost normalized

If you go out to a popular club or bar you have a very high likelihood of seeing women dressed in a way that can easily trigger lust in men

As a woman, being lusted over might even trigger primal brain chemicals like dopamine and could become addictive


For me, understanding lust as a sin makes me more aware of my own fleshly desires and makes lustful messaging much more obvious when I see it in our culture. it's everywhere when you see it for what it is



Summary: 

